The pain of any human being anywhere in the world causes sorrow for a fellow human being.  The sight of a child losing his life in the presence of his loved ones, a mother whose joy for her family turns into mourning, a husband who is rushing the lifeless body of his spouse to some place and the spectator who does not know whether he will be seeing the final scene of life- these are scenes that rouse the emotions and feelings of any human being.  Anyone who has benefited from affection and humanity is affected and disturbed by witnessing these scenes- whether it occurs in France or in Palestine or Iraq or Lebanon or Syria.
.
Without a doubt, the one-and-a-half billion Muslims also have these feelings and abhor and are revolted by the perpetrators and those responsible for these calamities. The issue, however, is that if today’s pain is not used to build a better and safer future, then it will just turn into bitter and fruitless memories. I genuinely believe that it is only you youth who by learning the lessons of today’s hardship, have the power to discover new means for building the future and who can be barriers in the misguided path that has brought the west to its current impasse. 
#Jerman

Two weeks after the #ParisAttacks, a national memorial service was held to remember and honor the victims. President Hollande also asked citizens to display the "tricolore" to show solidarity, with a big social media campaign to encourage citizens to show the flag #fiersdelafrance (Proud of France). Patriotism and demand for flags has skyrocketed since the attacks and some people were forced to get creative, like one of the neighbors. Unlike in the US where the flag is commonly displayed outside and inside homes, displaying the flag in France outside your home usually meant you leaned to the far-right in the political spectrum. That taboo might be on its way out--two thirds of people surveyed last week said that they appreciate seeing the flag flying on homes and gardens "√† la mode americaine," and most indicated that the flag represents the nation and its values over any political allegiance.

On the 27th of November 2014, I went to see Ed Sheeran at Le Bataclan. It was my first time seeing him live and my first time at this venue. I'll cherish the memories I have of that night forever, because I felt so good out there with all these people coming for the same reason I did: to celebrate and appreciate an artist and his music. So today, as France pays tribute to the victims of the attacks which occurred two weeks ago in Paris and at Le Bataclan, I cannot but hurt once more and pray for all the families and friends who lost a dear one, pray for peace and justice. But today, I also smile remembering the fun I had a year ago with two of my friends. So here's a picture I took, and here's a video I took. You'll notice I was shaking, just like thousand people did two weeks ago not knowing if they'd make it out alive, but I was shaking because I was living the music, and that's all they had come down for as well. data.text: No one should be shamed for grieving over mass murder...or for not grieving over the *right* mass murder. People in America got upset over France because it is relevant to our lives. Things that happen in the western world get more air time because we live in the western world and terrorist attacks are unusual for this hemisphere. Something that happens in Lebanon or Africa isn't going to be focused on as much by our community because it doesn't connect to our society and because those are regions with much higher frequencies of terrorist threat/attacks. (Not saying this is right, but I am saying this is the actual reason why this happens) Also take into consideration how many people TRULY read the news....we have access to millions of news stories online yet most people are only going to select the ones that are 1. Most relevant to themselves and 2. Easiest to come by. The media plays a role in this by selectively reporting certain things more so than others, but it doesn't mean that other attacks/events are any less important or horrific.

@thisiscaitland true ... true. An indictment of specific people; it was not. A deliberate attack at ingrained practice (although unchanged by society at large ... ) is exactly what it was. Because what is the media but the people? The people are the media; we, society, literally make it or break it. I agree with you, no one should be slandered because of their perceived lack of empathy ... but I would argue that people should continually practice empathy or solidarity regardless of their hemisphere consistently. It's like ... it bothers me that, a judeo Christian nation like ours ... would only do the whole solidarity thing (I'm talking in genuine zeal like the recent Paris tragedy) for a fellow (traditionally) judeo Christian nation; like France. Or it appears to be the case ... and to your point; the media (of which the people are part of ... but there are of course levels of dubious intent) is the instrument to be blamed; for what I can only describe as ... the occasional veneer of genuine humanity. That's the problem. But human beings, people, us, are the problem and the only solution ... in my opinion. How we (society/humanity) get there effectively and genuinely will address many social ills ... but may take time. I know it'll be worth it but people need to be reminded every now and then. caption.text: It was late last Friday night when i found myself on a mission hiking up Temescal canyon to do some light painting photography with my friend @roro_310_  we stopped off on this first little perched out area that overlooked west LA and As I was setting up the camera trying to think of what to do my mind kept drawing a blank! I had absolutely nothing in me to get my artistic juices flowing so I let my friend Roman try some stuff out so he could learn how to light paint! As we bounced around we moved to this tree and skyline that he starting painting with some blues, reds, whites and greens. Well as soon as the photo processed and I saw the blue, red, and white it all dawned on me of what my move was gonna be and that was something that represented #FRANCE cuz of all the horrible stuff they had just gone through during that very tragic day! So with that going through my head we flew over to this bench and told Roman my idea of what I wanted to do he went to town several times on this pic before it came out the way we wanted it to but it came out perfect! When I express myself in photography art these days I would like it to have some meaning or beauty behind it and if I can show my support for all of France's losses over there and to also let them know our prayers go out to the loved ones who lost family or friends to people with such hate in them and who have no respect for human life and live with no remorse for the disgusting things they do its just fucking sad that we people just don't wanna get along and be symbiotic with one another! #porteouverte #parisattacks #prayforparis #paris #help #support #lovenothate #onelove #art #lightpainting #longexposure #malibu #temescalcanyon #nightphotography #expressyourself #losangeles #nighthike #hike #photography #picoftheday #photooftheday #europe

[Article Written For @rivardreport on #ParisAttacks]

It has now been a week since the attacks on Paris, the place my #SanAntonian husband has called home for the past 12 years. A place I more recently named my home.

The news has been alight with action film-esqe captures of the attackers alleged to have caused the horrific tragedy so recently passed. The rash President of the #Republique, like the #Bush who burned before him, speaks words familiar. Sends #bombs. Wages #war.

But there are no celebrations here. Unmoved, #Parisians react with #ambivalence.

They’re not na√Øve enough to think the captures of these criminals will change anything. It certainty won’t bring back the lives lost, nor prevent similar horrors from occurring. Nor are they #na√Øve enough to think small men with big bombs will fix their problems either.

So they lay #flowers, light #candles, and quietly, with sorrow and #defiance in their eyes, celebrate life again. As they always have and always will. Their #solidarity stated in unity from freshly painted walls throughout the city “#FluctuatNecMergitur” it reads, “tossed by the waves but not sunk”. But the world does not follow suit. The media sensationalises. And on the walls of a world in which people hide their faces behind photos hued in red, white and blue, a different reaction ensues, fuelled by the very impulse of #ignorance and #hatred, which reaped death on these streets.

They blame #Refugees (those who flee their home country due to heinous acts of terror) and #Muslims (1.57 billion people who couldn't possibly "all be #terrorists" or "we" would all be very extinct) for these acts of terror, and in their reactive generalizations, they support the very fear, hatred and #violence they attempt to condemn. Ignorantly, they promote the next tragedy. Ignorantly, they feed the anger resting inside the dormant #souls of those who commit crimes like these.
